Guard pylsp_definitions against jedi definitions with no source position.

When follow_builtin_definitions is True (the default) the filter short-circuits
`(follow_builtin_defns or _not_internal_definition(d))`, so the
_not_internal_definition guard — the only check for `d.line is not None` — never
runs. A jedi definition resolving into a builtin/compiled module has
`d.line == None`, which then crashes at `d.line - 1` with
`TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for -: 'NoneType' and 'int'`.

A definition with no line/column can't produce a valid LSP range anyway, so
exclude it unconditionally. Upstream: python-lsp-server pylsp_definitions.

--- a/pylsp/plugins/definition.py
+++ b/pylsp/plugins/definition.py
@@ -73,3 +73,6 @@
         for d in definitions
-        if d.is_definition() and (follow_builtin_defns or _not_internal_definition(d))
+        if d.is_definition()
+        and d.line is not None
+        and d.column is not None
+        and (follow_builtin_defns or _not_internal_definition(d))
     ]
